ook, Somerset, England":"Wambrook, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Belet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Slovenian and Croatian: nickname for a fair-skinned or fair-haired man, derived from Slovenian and dialectal Croatian <i>bel</i> ‘white, light, fair’. Compare   Belitz   3 and   Beltz   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Belitz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dietrich, Gunter, Hans, Kurt.","Jewish (from Belarus and Ukraine): habitational name for someone from Belitsa in Belarus.","German: habitational name from Belitz (Mecklenburg-West Pomerania, Lower Saxony) or Beelitz (Saxony-Anhalt, Brandenburg)."]},{"name":"Beltz","meanings":["South German: metonymic occupational name for a furrier, from Middle High German <i>bel(lī)z</i> ‘fur, skin’ (from Late Latin <i>pellicia</i>).","In some cases also a Germanized or Americanized form of Slovenian   Belec   or its variant <b>Belc</b>."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   contain